context: The <a0_1><b5_0>pound-force<b5_0/><a0_1/> has a metric counterpart, less commonly used than the newton: <a0_4>the <a0_0><a0_2><a0_3><b6_0>kilogram-force<b6_0/><a0_3/><a0_0/> (<a0_4/>kgf)<a0_2/> (sometimes <a1_0><a1_1><a1_2><a1_3><a1_4>kilopond<a1_4/><a1_3/><a1_2/><a1_1/><a1_0/>), is the force exerted by standard gravity on one kilogram of mass. The <b7_0>kilogram-force<b7_0/> leads to an alternate, but rarely used unit of mass: <a2_4>the <a2_1><a2_2><a2_3>metric <a2_0>slug<a2_4/><a2_3/><a2_2/><a2_1/><a2_0/> (sometimes mug or hyl) is that mass that accelerates at 1 m·s−2 when subjected to a force of 1 kgf. The <b8_0>kilogram-force<b8_0/> is not a part of the modern SI system, and is generally deprecated; however it still sees use for some purposes as expressing aircraft weight, jet thrust, bicycle spoke tension, torque wrench settings and engine output torque. Other arcane units of force include the <a4_0><a4_1><a4_2><a4_3><a4_4>sthène<a4_4/><a4_3/><a4_2/><a4_1/><a4_0/>, which is equivalent to 1000 N, and the <a3_0><a3_1><a3_2><a3_3><a3_4>kip<a3_4/><a3_3/><a3_2/><a3_1/><a3_0/>, which is equivalent to 1000 lbf.
